Perfect. That’s exactly the right moment to pause and integrate. You’ve built many moving parts—agents, services, routes, realtime, analytics, surveys, tasks. Before adding the chat interface and proactive agent results, we need to verify the system behaves as one organism, not a pile of modules. Think of it as aligning the nervous system before adding higher cognition.

Here’s how we’ll proceed when you send the code.

First, I’ll perform a full architectural integration review. That means checking the whole stack against your database schema and your intended workflow.

Things I will verify:

Database alignment
Every table in your schema must have a corresponding model and must actually be written to somewhere in the code. That includes:

complaints

complaint_analysis

workflow_events

tasks

notifications

infrastructure_alerts

feedback

complaint_status_history

complaint_embeddings

event_queue

zones

users

contractors

departments

assets

If a table exists but nothing inserts into it, we fix that.

Agent orchestration correctness
The LangGraph orchestrator must ensure the following flow happens automatically:

Complaint created
→ routing agent classification
→ geo infrastructure mapping
→ complaint_analysis row written
→ workflow_events logged
→ task created
→ predictive clustering triggered
→ notifications sent

We will confirm each step updates the DB.

Event logging completeness
Every meaningful state transition should generate a row in:

workflow_events

Example events that must exist:

COMPLAINT_RECEIVED
AI_CLASSIFIED
ASSET_MAPPED
TASK_CREATED
TASK_STATUS_UPDATED
SURVEY_REQUESTED
SURVEY_SUBMITTED
CLUSTER_ALERT

If any are missing, we add them.

API completeness
For the prototype you should have APIs for:

Complaints

create complaint

get complaint

update complaint status

list complaints (zone filtered)

Tasks

create task

update task

employee tasks

contractor stats

Surveys

submit feedback

get survey status

Analytics

department stats

zone stats

contractor performance

heatmap

alerts

SLA metrics

Dashboard

role aware dashboard

Assistant

query endpoint

Realtime

websocket endpoint

If any CRUD endpoints are missing, we add them.

Zone-based security
Your admin / employee / citizen logic must enforce:

Super admin → department scope
Admin → zone scope
Employee → assigned tasks only
Citizen → own complaints

I’ll confirm the filters exist in SQL queries.

Realtime integration
We will confirm that these services emit websocket events:

Complaint creation
Task creation
Task status update
Cluster detection
Notification creation

So the frontend receives proactive updates.

Predictive system integration
The predictive agent must actually run after complaints are processed and must insert rows into:

infrastructure_alerts

If it currently runs only manually, we wire it into the orchestrator.

Embedding pipeline check
You created:

complaint_embeddings

I’ll confirm that complaint embeddings are actually being generated and inserted, otherwise the table is unused.

Admin AI assistant tool access
The assistant must be able to access:

analytics
complaints search
contractor stats
zone data

If tools are incomplete we extend them.

Chat + proactive results plan
After integration is verified we will implement two APIs:

Agent Chat API
This allows admins to ask questions.

POST /api/assistant/chat

Agent Results Feed
This returns proactive outputs from agents.

GET /api/agents/insights

The insights endpoint will aggregate:

cluster alerts
underperforming contractors
high complaint zones
recent AI classifications

This becomes the “AI insights panel” on your dashboard.